      • decomposeForLoop

        public void decomposeForLoop(org.eclipse.emf.ecore.resource.ResourceSet rs)
        Replace a ForStatement with an equivalent WhileStatement

        A ForStatement has the following structure: 

           "for" "(" initExpression=ForInitStatment condExpression=Expression ";" loopExpression=StatementNoColon? ")"
     loopBody=BlockStatement;
        The decomposition will result in the following structure: 
            ForInitStatment
    "while (" condExpression ") {"
      loopBody.stats
      loopExpression
    "}"
        Parameters:
        rs - the ResourceSet of the project

      • _compile

        protected MetaData _compile(ReturnStatement retStat,
                            java.util.HashMap<java.lang.String,MetaData> map)
        Compile a ReturnStatement.

        This function behaves differently depending on whether the contain operation is "main". If it is the main operation, the returned values are written to the shared memory. Otherwise, it is returned in the form of a MetaData.

        Parameters:
        stat - an AST node of ReturnStatement type
        map - the symbol table of current operation
        Returns:

      • _compile

        protected MetaData _compile(WhileStatement whileStatement,
                            java.util.HashMap<java.lang.String,MetaData> map)
        Compile a WhileStatement.

        We try to unroll the loop up to Configuration.maxUnrolling times. Beyond that, the loop keeps its original form, i.e., consisting of a branch instruction and several labels.

        The unrolling is only possible when the condition is constant, i.e., can be evaluated during compilation time.

        Parameters:
        whileStatement - an AST node of WhileStatement type
        map - the symbol table of current operation
        Returns:
        null

        protected MetaData _compile(IfStatement stat,

        Compile an IfStatement.

      • _compile

        protected MetaData _compile(ArrayAccess exp,
                            java.util.HashMap<java.lang.String,MetaData> map)
        Compile an ArrayAccess expression.

        This function is implemented considering mainly three cases:

        1. If the the array and the index are both known at compilation time, the corresponding MetaData is returned immediately. Otherwise, for the other two cases, eQASM instructions are generated.

        2. In most situation, except for case 3, the function returns the indexed element in the array (encapsulate in a MetaData). This element can be a primitive value or an address that represents another array.

        3. If the array consists of primitive values, but it is on the left side of an assignment statement, the function should not return the indexed value, but the indexed address. We created a PointerType MetaData for expressing that address

        Parameters:
        exp - an AST node of ArrayAccess type
        map - the symbol table of current operation
        Returns:
        the MetaData that contains the compilation result

      • compileFunctionCall

        public MetaData compileFunctionCall(Variable nodeVariable,
                                    org.eclipse.emf.common.util.EList<Expression> pars,
                                    java.util.HashMap<java.lang.String,MetaData> map,
                                    org.eclipse.xtext.nodemodel.ICompositeNode node)
        Implement a function (operation) call.

      • allocHeapForArrayBody

        public void allocHeapForArrayBody(Type typeElement,
                                  MetaData metaNumOfElements)
        Allocate a piece of heap space to store an array body

        The structure of an array is: `[ length(=n), ele_0, ele_1, ele_2, ..., ele_{n-1} ]`. This operation shifts the heap pointer by NumOfBytes = INT_SIZE + NumOfElements * NumOfBytesPerElement where the extra INT_SIZE is used to store the length of the array.

        Parameters:
        typeElement - the type of the element
        metaNumOfElements - the MetaData storing the array length
